Bring a large #pot{} of water to the boil with @salt{1/4%tsp}. Wash the @new potatoes{1.5}(washed but skin on) but leave the nutritious skin on. Cut the potatoes into eighths and cook in the boiling water for ~{10-15%mins} until cooked through. Drain and allow to cool slightly.

Bring another pot of water to the boil with @salt{1/4%tsp}. Add the @sugar snap peas{1} and boil rapidly for ~{2%mins} until al dente (which means they still have a bit of crunch to them). Immediately drain the sugar snap peas and put in a #bowl{} of cold water to stop them overcooking.

Make a vinaigrette by mixing the @wholegrain mustard{1} with the juice from @lemon{1/2}(juiced) and @salt{1/4%tsp} and some @black pepper{}. Slowly mix in @olive oil{2%tbsp}.

> Tip: If you have some, add 1⁄2 tsp of honey to the mustard or 1⁄2 tsp of sugar to sweeten the vinaigrette.

Toast your @pine nuts{1} by putting them in a dry #frying pan{} on a medium heat.

> Tip: Watch them like an impatient driver watches a red traffic light, as they can burn easily.

Roughly chop half of the @mint{3}(roughly chopped, half whole and half chopped) leaves and leave the rest whole.

Mix the @pea shoots and baby leaves{1}, cooked potatoes, sugar snap peas, whole mint leaves and chopped mint. Pour over as much vinaigrette as you like (keep any remainder for future salads).

> Tip: Try splitting some of the sugar snap peas in half for those extra presentation points!

Divide the salad between your bowls then crumble over the @goat's cheese{4}(crumbled) and sprinkle over the toasted pine nuts.